coding obstruction for the m=1 specialization of Reed-) Tj\n-72 -385 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 370 Td (Solomon codes. Let C = RS[F_q,L,k] with |L|=n. We prove that, whenever q > binom\\(n,k+1\\),) Tj\n-72 -370 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 355 Td (there exists a received word y for which the Hamming ball of radius n-k contains exactly) Tj\n-72 -355 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 340 Td (binom\\(n,k\\) Reed-Solomon codewords. Consequently, if binom\\(n,k+1\\) < q < 2^128 binom\\(n,k\\),) Tj\n-72 -340 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 325 Td (then |Lambda\\(C,y,n-k\\)| = binom\\(n,k\\) > 2^-128 |F_q|. Thus the epsilon_star = 2^-128 threshold) Tj\n-72 -325 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 310 Td (fails at delta = 1-k/n for the m=1 specialization in this field-size window.) Tj\n-72 -310 Td\n/F2 13 Tf\n72 285 Td (1. Scope of the Claim) Tj\n-72 -285 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 263 Td (This draft addresses the m=1 specialization of the grand list-decoding challenge. In this) Tj\n-72 -263 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 248 Td (specialization, Lambda\\(C,delta\\) is the ordinary Reed-Solomon list at relative Hamming radius) Tj\n-72 -248 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 233 Td (delta. The draft does not assert a result for arbitrary constant m unless an explicit m-wise) Tj\n-72 -233 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 218 Td (extension is added.) Tj\n-72 -218 Td\n/F2 13 Tf\n72 193 Td (2. Notation) Tj\n-72 -193 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 171 Td (Let F_q be a finite field and let L subset F_q be an evaluation domain of size n. Let) Tj\n-72 -171 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 156 Td (RS[F_q,L,k] denote the Reed-Solomon code obtained by evaluating polynomials of degree less) Tj\n-72 -156 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 141 Td (than k on L. The rate is rho = k/n. For a received word y in F_q^n and integer radius r, let) Tj\n-72 -141 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 126 Td (Lambda\\(C,y,r\\) be the set of codewords of C within Hamming distance r from y.) Tj\n-72 -126 Td\n/F2 13 Tf\n72 101 Td (3. Main Theorem) Tj\n-72 -101 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 79 Td (Let C = RS[F_q,L,k] with |L|=n. Suppose q > binom\\(n,k+1\\). Then there exists y in F_q^n such) Tj\n-72 -79 Td\nET\nendstream\nendobj\n4 0 obj\n<< /Length 3623 >>\nstream\nBT\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 742 Td (that |Lambda\\(C,y,n-k\\)| = binom\\(n,k\\). Consequently, if q < 2^128 binom\\(n,k\\), then) Tj\n-72 -742 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 727 Td (|Lambda\\(C,y,n-k\\)| > 2^-128 |F_q| at delta = 1-k/n.) Tj\n-72 -727 Td\n/F2 13 Tf\n72 702 Td (4. Proof) Tj\n-72 -702 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 680 Td (Choose y in F_q^n such that no polynomial of degree less than k agrees with y on more than k) Tj\n-72 -680 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 665 Td (coordinates. Section 5 proves that such y exists when q > binom\\(n,k+1\\).) Tj\n-72 -665 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 640 Td (For each k-subset S of the n coordinate positions, there is a unique degree < k polynomial) Tj\n-72 -640 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 625 Td (f_S interpolating y on S. Its Reed-Solomon codeword agrees with y on S, hence has Hamming) Tj\n-72 -625 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 610 Td (distance at most n-k from y.) Tj\n-72 -610 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 585 Td (If two distinct k-subsets S and T produced the same polynomial, then that polynomial would) Tj\n-72 -585 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 570 Td (agree with y on S union T. Since S and T are distinct k-subsets, S union T has more than k) Tj\n-72 -570 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 555 Td (coordinates. This contradicts the choice of y. Therefore the binom\\(n,k\\) k-subsets produce) Tj\n-72 -555 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 540 Td (binom\\(n,k\\) distinct codewords in Lambda\\(C,y,n-k\\).) Tj\n-72 -540 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 515 Td (Conversely, any codeword in Lambda\\(C,y,n-k\\) agrees with y on at least k coordinates. By) Tj\n-72 -515 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 500 Td (construction, no degree < k polynomial agrees with y on more than k coordinates. Therefore) Tj\n-72 -500 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 485 Td (each listed codeword agrees on exactly k coordinates and is generated by one of the) Tj\n-72 -485 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 470 Td (k-subsets above. Hence |Lambda\\(C,y,n-k\\)| = binom\\(n,k\\).) Tj\n-72 -470 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 445 Td (If q < 2^128 binom\\(n,k\\), then binom\\(n,k\\) > 2^-128 q = 2^-128 |F_q|. Thus the threshold) Tj\n-72 -445 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 430 Td (|Lambda| <= 2^-128 |F_q| fails at delta = 1-k/n.) Tj\n-72 -430 Td\n/F2 13 Tf\n72 405 Td (5. Existence Lemma) Tj\n-72 -405 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 383 Td (Choose y uniformly at random from F_q^n. Fix a degree < k polynomial f and a fixed) Tj\n-72 -383 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 368 Td (\\(k+1\\)-subset T of coordinates. The probability that f agrees with y on every coordinate of T) Tj\n-72 -368 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 353 Td (is q^{-\\(k+1\\)}. There are q^k degree < k polynomials and binom\\(n,k+1\\) choices for T. By the) Tj\n-72 -353 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 338 Td (union bound, the probability that some degree < k polynomial agrees with y on more than k) Tj\n-72 -338 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 323 Td (coordinates is at most binom\\(n,k+1\\)/q. If q > binom\\(n,k+1\\), this probability is less than 1,) Tj\n-72 -323 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 308 Td (so a suitable y exists.) Tj\n-72 -308 Td\n/F2 13 Tf\n72 283 Td (6. Fixed-Rate Examples) Tj\n-72 -283 Td\n/F2 11 Tf\n72 261 Td (rho = 1/2) Tj\n-72 -261 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 243 Td (- n = 32) Tj\n-72 -243 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 228 Td (- k = 16) Tj\n-72 -228 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 213 Td (- delta = 16/32) Tj\n-72 -213 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 198 Td (- radius = 16) Tj\n-72 -198 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 183 Td (- exact list size = 601080390) Tj\n-72 -183 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 168 Td (- existence threshold: q > 565722720) Tj\n-72 -168 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 153 Td (- threshold failure condition: q < 2^128 * 601080390) Tj\n-72 -153 Td\n/F2 11 Tf\n72 128 Td (rho = 1/4) Tj\n-72 -128 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 110 Td (- n = 32) Tj\n-72 -110 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 95 Td (- k = 8) Tj\n-72 -95 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 80 Td (- delta = 24/32) Tj\n-72 -80 Td\nET\nendstream\nendobj\n5 0 obj\n<< /Length 2980 >>\nstream\nBT\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 742 Td (- radius = 24) Tj\n-72 -742 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 727 Td (- exact list size = 10518300) Tj\n-72 -727 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 712 Td (- existence threshold: q > 28048800) Tj\n-72 -712 Td\n/F1 10 Tf\n72 697 Td (- threshold failure condi